[[File:Margaux94 1.jpg|right|thumb|upright|[[Ch<U+00E2>teau Margaux]], a [[First Growth]] from the Bordeaux region of France, is highly collectible.]]

==Collecting==
{{See also|Aging of wine|Investment wine|Storage of wine}}
Outstanding vintages from the best vineyards may sell for thousands of [[United States dollar|dollars]] per bottle, though the broader term "fine wine" covers those typically retailing in excess of US$30<U+2013>50.<ref>For example, [[Berry Brothers & Rudd]], one of the world's largest dealers, start "fine wine" prices at about <U+00A3>25<U+2014>in March 2009 with a wine from [[Au Bon Climat]] [http://www.bbr.com/fine-wine/offers website "Fine wine offers"].</ref> "[[Investment wine]]s" are considered by some to be [[Veblen good]]s: those for which demand increases rather than decreases as their prices rise. 
Particular selections have higher value, such as "Verticals", in which a range of vintages of a specific grape and vineyard, are offered. The most notable was a [[Ch%C3%A2teau_d%27Yquem#Since_1968|Chateau d'Yquem]] 135 year vertical containing every vintage from 1860 to 2003 sold for $1.5 million.
The most common wines purchased for investment include those from [[Bordeaux wine|Bordeaux]] and [[Burgundy wine|Burgundy]]; [[cult wine]]s from [[Europe]] and elsewhere; and [[Port wine|vintage port]]. Characteristics of highly collectible wines include:

#A proven track record of holding well over time
#A drinking-window plateau (i.e., the period for maturity and approachability) that is many years long
#A consensus among experts as to the quality of the wines
#Rigorous production methods at every stage, including grape selection and appropriate barrel aging

Investment in fine wine has attracted those who take advantage of their victims' relative ignorance of this wine market sector.<ref>economist.com [http://www.economist.com/node/18836894 Fine-wine fraud].</ref> Such [[wine fraud]]sters often profit by charging excessively high prices for off-vintage or lower-status wines from well-known wine regions, while claiming that they are offering a sound investment unaffected by [[economic cycle]]s. As with any investment, thorough research is essential to making an informed decision.

==Production==
{{Main|Winemaking}}
{{See also|List of wine-producing countries|List of wine-producing regions}}
In 2012, Italy was the top producer of wine in the world, followed by France, Spain, the United States and Argentina.{{citation needed|date=August 2013}}

